Author-Name:  Scharfstein, David S
Title:   Optimal Debt Structure and the Number of Creditors. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 1-25
Issue: 1
Volume: 104
Year: 1996
Month:  February 
Abstract:
  Within an optimal contracting framework, the authors analyze the optimal
 number of creditors a company borrows from. They also analyze the optimal
 allocation of security interests among creditors and intercreditor voting
 rules that govern rule renegotiation of debt contracts. The key to the
 authors' analysis is the idea that these aspects of the debt structure
 affect the outcome of debt renegotiation following a default. Debt
 structures that lead to inefficient renegotiation are beneficial in that
 they deter default but they are also costly if default is beyond a
 manager's control. The optimal debt structure balances these effects.  Copyright 1996 by University of Chicago Press.
